     unsigned quantities. These functions behave as if the value was
     "cast" to the corresponding unsigned C type, and are most useful
     for dealing with unsigned integers returned by external C
     routines. The routines always use the smallest Pure int type
     capable of holding the result: `int' for *note ubyte: 148. and
     *note ushort: 149, `bigint' for *note uint: 14a, *note uint64:
     14b. and *note ulong: 14c. All routines take int parameters. In
     the case of *note uint64: 14b, a bigint parameter is also
     permitted (which is what the C interface returns for 64 bit
     values). Also note that *note ulong: 14c. reduces to either *note
     uint: 14a. or *note uint64: 14b, depending on the size of `long'
     for the host architecture.

